"script": "If a star exploded right next to you in space, you'd hear absolutely nothing. That's because sound needs a material to travel through, like air or water, vibrating from one molecule to the next until it reaches your ear. But space is a near-perfect vacuum, almost completely empty, so there's nothing to carry the wave. The most violent blast in the universe happens in total silence. This is why astronauts on a spacewalk can only talk through radios. And it means supernovas, tearing whole stars apart, unfold without making a single sound.",
